RSV (AREXVY) - Exposure via skin contact

Data Lock Point: 2024_02_23

1 Quantitative Signal status

1.1 Disproportionality

The vaccine-event combination RSV (AREXVY) - Exposure via skin contact was a signal of disproportionate reporting with an EB05 value of 2.89.

The threshold for being flagged as a signal of disproportionate reporting is an EB05>=2 meaning that there there is a 95% probability that the reporting of Exposure via skin contact was at least twice post exposure to RSV (AREXVY) than post all vaccines [1]. Under the assumption of no causality between RSV (AREXVY) and Exposure via skin contact and no bias it would have been expected to observe an EBGM of 1.

It means that the quantified causality criterion of strength of association is met.

It is to be noted that the nature of the spontaneous report does not provide reliable estimates of the strength of association (whatever the choice of the disproportionality method) and that some reporting bias or difference in demographic characteristics might explain the (un)observed disproportion.

1.2 Time-to-onset

The vaccine-event combination RSV (AREXVY) - Exposure via skin contact was not a signal of unexpected time-to-onset distribution with a p-value of the two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test being 1 and distance between the two empirical cumulative distributions being of 4.8523207%.

The TTO signal detection method tests if the distribution of Exposure via skin contact post RSV (AREXVY) is significantly different from the distribution of Exposure via skin contact post other vaccines using a two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test [2]. The threshold for being flagged as a signal of unexpected time-to-onset distribution is a P-value <0.001 and a distance between the two empirical distributions larger than 20%. Under the assumption of no causality and no bias, it would have been expected that the time-to-onset distribution for Exposure via skin contact would have been the same post RSV (AREXVY) than post other vaccines.

It means that the quantified causality criterion of temporality is not met.

It is to be noted that the nature of the spontaneous report does not provide reliable estimates of the temporal relationship between the exposure and the occurrence of the events as there is the reporting bias over time: the latter the event occurs after exposure, the less chance it has to be reported. Other biases could distort the reported time-to-onset distribution (media attention, etc.)

1.3 Overall

Based on the screening of the Empirical Bayes Geometric Mean (EBGM) and the screening of the time-to-onset distribution,the vaccine-event combination RSV (AREXVY) - Exposure via skin contact is considered as quantitative signal.

3 Case series

3.1 Characterization of the case series using vigipoint

Vigipoint [3] provides a way to pinpoint key features within the vaccine-event case series RSV (AREXVY) - Exposure via skin contact which are imbalanced (either with excess or deficit) compared to what you would expect looking at how these features are globally distributed within RSV (AREXVY).

3.2 Seriousness

A total of 14 reports of Exposure via skin contact were received post exposure to RSV (AREXVY). Among them:

  • 0 (0.0 %) were fatal cases.
  • 0 (0.0 %) were life threatening cases.
  • 0 (0.0 %) were hospitalized cases.
  • 0 (0.0 %) were emergency room cases.
  • 0 (0.0 %) were cases with disabilies.

There are no new cases received since last data refresh.

3.3 Demographic characteristics

14 cases of Exposure via skin contact post RSV (AREXVY) were reported in VAERS:

  • Among them, there were 9 (64.3%) female cases and 3 (21.4%) male cases while the overall female:male ratio is 67:26%.

  • The mean (median) age for patients presenting symptoms of Exposure via skin contact was 71 (72) years while the overall mean (median) age was 70 (71) years.

  • The top 5 contributing US states for patients presenting symptoms of Exposure via skin contact were MI ( 28.6 %) , NY ( 28.6 %) , CT ( 7.1 %) , GA ( 7.1 %) , MN ( 7.1 %) while overall the top 5 of contributing US states are NA ( 13 %) , FL ( 8.8 %) , CA ( 8.3 %) , NY ( 5.8 %) , TX ( 4.3 %)

6 Disclaimer

This analysis is exploratory only and authors cannot be held responsible for any decision made using these data. It is important to distinguish quantitative signals such as disproportionate reporting, unexpected time-to-onset patterns or cluster from safety signals. Only a qualitative review using multiple data source (literature, clinical trials, etc.) and multiple causality criteria assessment could qualify quantitative signals into safety signals.
